                </fo:inline> on why they chose Bodington gave 'open access by default' and the
                ability 'to edit permissions by individual' (i.e. not 'pigeonhole' people in roles),
                as major reasons for choosing Bodington over commercial VLEs.<fo:block
                    space-before="1em" space-after="1em" role="p"/><fo:inline font-style="italic"
                    role="i"> How does this fit with Phytopedia's request for release dates on Wiki
                    pages? </fo:inline><fo:block space-before="1em" space-after="1em" role="p"
                    /><fo:inline font-weight="bolder" role="b">
                    <fo:inline font-style="italic" role="i">HT</fo:inline>
                </fo:inline> Having said all this, I (an ex-Eng Lit student) have just spent a happy
                half-hour on the Phytopedia site finding out how plants survive in deserts. If
                things go the way of Phytopedia, I wonder if we will eventually end up with a
                wonderful academic resource which <fo:inline font-style="italic" role="i"
                >should</fo:inline> be available to university members in the spirit of academic
                enquiry. I agree that students discussions or first drafts aren't in this category,
                but I think that perhaps lecture notes should be.<fo:block space-before="1em"
                    space-after="1em" role="p"/><fo:inline font-weight="bolder" role="b"
                >RW</fo:inline> but teaching staff, esp hourly-paid ones, may assert rights over
                their material. Also, breaches of copyright would become much more visible. This is
                a bigger battle....<fo:block space-before="1em" space-after="1em" role="p"
                    /><fo:inline font-weight="bolder" role="b">HT</fo:inline> very true, Rhiannon,
